					<div id=3D"mw-content-text" class=3D"mw-body-content"><div class=3D"mw=
-content-ltr mw-parser-output" lang=3D"en" dir=3D"ltr"><div class=3D"shortd=
escription nomobile noexcerpt noprint searchaux" style=3D"display:none">Sta=
tic pressure exerted by the weight of the Earth's atmosphere</div>
<div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">"Air pressur=
e" redirects here. For the pressure of air in other systems, see <a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pressure" title=3D"Pressure">Pressure</a>.</=
div>
<p><b>Atmospheric pressure</b>, also known as <b>air pressure</b> or <b>bar=
ometric pressure</b> (after the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ba=
rometer" title=3D"Barometer">barometer</a>), is the <a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Pressure" title=3D"Pressure">pressure</a> within the <a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Atmosphere_of_Earth" title=3D"Atmosphe=
re of Earth">atmosphere of Earth</a>. The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Standard_atmosphere_(unit)" title=3D"Standard atmosphere (unit)">st=
andard atmosphere</a> (symbol: atm) is a unit of pressure defined as 101,32=
5&nbsp;<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pascal_(unit)" title=3D"Pas=
cal (unit)">Pa</a> (1,013.25&nbsp;<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Pascal_(unit)" title=3D"Pascal (unit)">hPa</a>), which is equivalent to 1,0=
13.25 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bar_(unit)" title=3D"Bar (un=
it)">millibars</a>, 760<span class=3D"nowrap">&nbsp;</span><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Millimetre_of_mercury" title=3D"Millimetre of merc=
ury">mm Hg</a>, 29.9212<span class=3D"nowrap">&nbsp;</span><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Inch_of_mercury" title=3D"Inch of mercury">inches<=
span class=3D"nowrap">&nbsp;</span>Hg</a>, or 14.696<span class=3D"nowrap">=
&nbsp;</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pounds_per_square_inc=
h" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Pounds per square inch">psi</a>.<sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-ICAO_1-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Atmospheric_pressure#cite_note-ICAO-1"><span class=3D"cite-bracket=
">[</span>1<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The atm unit is =
roughly equivalent to the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mean_sea=
-level" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Mean sea-level">mean sea-level</a> a=
tmospheric pressure on Earth; that is, the Earth's atmospheric pressure at =
sea level is approximately 1 atm.=20
</p><p>In most circumstances, atmospheric pressure is closely approximated =
by the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fluid_pressure" class=3D"mw=
-redirect" title=3D"Fluid pressure">hydrostatic pressure</a> caused by the =
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Weight" title=3D"Weight">weight</a=
> of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Earth%27s_atmosphere" class=
=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Earth's atmosphere">air</a> above the measurement=
 point. As <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Elevation" title=3D"Ele=
vation">elevation</a> increases, there is less overlying atmospheric mass, =
so atmospheric pressure decreases with increasing elevation. Because the at=
mosphere is thin relative to the Earth's radius=E2=80=94especially the dens=
e atmospheric layer at low altitudes=E2=80=94the Earth's <a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gravitational_acceleration" title=3D"Gravitational a=
cceleration">gravitational acceleration</a> as a function of altitude can b=
e approximated as constant and contributes little to this fall-off. Pressur=
e measures force per unit area, with <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/International_System_of_Units" title=3D"International System of Units">S=
I units</a> of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pascal_(unit)" titl=
e=3D"Pascal (unit)">pascals</a> (1 pascal =3D 1 <a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Newton_(unit)" title=3D"Newton (unit)">newton</a> per square =
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Metre" title=3D"Metre">metre</a>, =
1<span class=3D"nowrap">&nbsp;</span>N/m<sup>2</sup>). On average, a column=
 of air with a cross-sectional area of 1 square <a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Centimetre" title=3D"Centimetre">centimetre</a> (cm<sup>2</su=
p>), measured from the mean (average) sea level to the top of Earth's atmos=
phere, has a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mass" title=3D"Mass">=
mass</a> of about 1.03 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kilogram" t=
itle=3D"Kilogram">kilogram</a> and exerts a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Force" title=3D"Force">force</a> or "weight" of about 10.1 <a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Newtons" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"=
Newtons">newtons</a>, resulting in a pressure of 10.1 N/cm<sup>2</sup> or 1=
01<span class=3D"nowrap">&nbsp;</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Newton_(unit)#Kilonewtons" title=3D"Newton (unit)">kN</a>/m<sup>2</sup>=
 (101 kilopascals, kPa). A column of air with a cross-sectional area of 1<s=
pan class=3D"nowrap">&nbsp;</span>in<sup>2</sup> would have a weight of abo=
ut 14.7<span class=3D"nowrap">&nbsp;</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Pound_(force)" title=3D"Pound (force)">lbf</a>, resulting in a pre=
ssure of 14.7<span class=3D"nowrap">&nbsp;</span>lbf/in<sup>2</sup>.
</p>
<meta property=3D"mw:PageProp/toc">
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Mechanism">Mechanism</h2><s=
pan class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span=
><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DAtmospheric_pressu=
re&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D1" title=3D"Edit section: Mechanism"><sp=
an>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></d=
iv>
<p>Atmospheric pressure is caused by the gravitational attraction of the pl=
anet on the atmospheric gases above the surface and is a function of the ma=
ss of the planet, the radius of the surface, and the amount and composition=
 of the gases and their vertical distribution in the atmosphere.<sup id=3D"=
cite_ref-2" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/At=
mospheric_pressure#cite_note-2"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>2<span=
 class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-3" class=3D"r=
eference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Atmospheric_pressure#cit=
e_note-3"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>3<span class=3D"cite-bracket=
">]</span></a></sup> It is modified by the planetary rotation and local eff=
ects such as wind velocity, density variations due to temperature and varia=
tions in composition.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-4" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Atmospheric_pressure#cite_note-4"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>4<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Mean_sea-level_pressure">Me=
an sea-level pressure</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-=
editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.ph=
p?title=3DAtmospheric_pressure&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D2" title=3D"=
Edit section: Mean sea-level pressure"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"=
mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size mw-halign-left" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Day5pressureforecast.png" clas=
s=3D"mw-file-description"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedi=
a/commons/thumb/a/ac/Day5pressureforecast.png/250px-Day5pressureforecast.pn=
g" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"250" height=3D"150" class=3D"mw-file-element=
" data-file-width=3D"1024" data-file-height=3D"613"></a><figcaption>Map sho=
wing atmospheric pressure in mbar or hPa</figcaption></figure>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Mslp-jja-djf.png" class=3D"mw-file-descriptio=
n"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/17/Ms=
lp-jja-djf.png/250px-Mslp-jja-djf.png" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"250" hei=
ght=3D"258" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"652" data-file-hei=
ght=3D"674"></a><figcaption>15-year average mean sea-level pressure for Jun=
e, July, and August (top) and December, January, and February (bottom). <a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ECMWF_re-analysis" title=3D"ECMWF re-=
analysis">ERA-15</a> re-analysis.</figcaption></figure>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Aircraft_altimeter.JPG" class=3D"mw-file-desc=
ription"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c=
/c6/Aircraft_altimeter.JPG/250px-Aircraft_altimeter.JPG" decoding=3D"async"=
 width=3D"250" height=3D"189" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"=
1632" data-file-height=3D"1232"></a><figcaption>Kollsman-type barometric ai=
rcraft <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Altimeter" title=3D"Altimet=
er">altimeter</a>.</figcaption></figure>
<p>The <i>mean sea-level pressure</i> (MSLP) is the atmospheric pressure at=
 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mean_sea_level" class=3D"mw-redir=
ect" title=3D"Mean sea level">mean sea level</a>. This is the atmospheric p=
ressure normally given in weather reports via meteorologists on radio, tele=
vision, and newspapers or on the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/I=
nternet" title=3D"Internet">Internet</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-5" class=3D"re=
ference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Atmospheric_pressure#cite=
_note-5"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>5<span class=3D"cite-bracket"=
>]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>The <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Altimeter_setting" t=
itle=3D"Altimeter setting">altimeter setting</a></i> in aviation is an atmo=
spheric pressure adjustment.
</p><p>Average <i>sea-level pressure</i> is 1,013.25&nbsp;hPa (29.921&nbsp;=
inHg; 760.00&nbsp;mmHg). In aviation weather reports (<a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/METAR" title=3D"METAR">METAR</a>), <a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/QNH" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"QNH">QNH</a> is tr=
ansmitted around the world in hectopascals or millibars (1 hectopascal =3D =
1 millibar). In the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/United_States"=
 title=3D"United States">United States</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Canada" title=3D"Canada">Canada</a>, and <a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Japan" title=3D"Japan">Japan</a> altimeter setting is repo=
rted in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Inches_of_mercury" class=
=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Inches of mercury">inches of mercury</a> (to two =
decimal places). The United States and Canada also report <i>sea-level pres=
sure</i> SLP, which is adjusted to sea level by a different method, in the =
remarks section, not in the internationally transmitted part of the code, i=
n hectopascals or millibars.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-6" class=3D"reference"><a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Atmospheric_pressure#cite_note-6"><spa=
n class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>6<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a>=
</sup> However, in Canada's public weather reports, sea level pressure is i=
nstead reported in kilopascals.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-7" class=3D"reference"><=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Atmospheric_pressure#cite_note-7"><=
span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>7<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span><=
/a></sup> In the US weather code remarks, three digits are all that are tra=
nsmitted; decimal points and the one or two most significant digits are omi=
tted: 1,013.2&nbsp;hPa (14.695&nbsp;psi) is transmitted as 132; 1,000&nbsp;=
hPa (100&nbsp;kPa) is transmitted as 000; 998.7<span class=3D"nowrap">&nbsp=
;</span>hPa is transmitted as 987; etc. A system transmitting the last thre=
e digits transmits the same code (800) for 1080.0 hPa as for 980.0 hPa.
</p><p>The highest <i>sea-level pressure</i> on Earth occurs in <a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Siberia" title=3D"Siberia">Siberia</a>, where=
 the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Siberian_High" title=3D"Siber=
ian High">Siberian High</a> often attains a <i>sea-level pressure</i> above=
 1,050&nbsp;hPa (15.2&nbsp;psi; 31&nbsp;inHg), with record highs close to 1=
,085&nbsp;hPa (15.74&nbsp;psi; 32.0&nbsp;inHg). The lowest measurable <i>se=
a-level pressure</i> is found at the centres of <a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Tropical_cyclone" title=3D"Tropical cyclone">tropical cyclone=
s</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tornado" title=3D"Tornad=
o">tornadoes</a>, with a <a class=3D"mw-selflink-fragment" href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Atmospheric_pressure#Records">record low</a> of 870&n=
bsp;hPa (12.6&nbsp;psi; 26&nbsp;inHg).=20
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Surface_pressure">Surface p=
ressure <span class=3D"anchor" id=3D"Surface"></span></h2><span class=3D"mw=
-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DAtmospheric_pressure&amp;action=
=3Dedit&amp;section=3D3" title=3D"Edit section: Surface pressure"><span>edi=
t</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
This section is about the atmospheric surface pressure. For other uses, see=
 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Surface_pressure_(disambiguation)=
" class=3D"mw-redirect mw-disambig" title=3D"Surface pressure (disambiguati=
on)">Surface pressure (disambiguation)</a>.</div>
<p><i>Surface pressure</i> is the atmospheric pressure at a location on <a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Earth" title=3D"Earth">Earth</a>'s su=
rface (<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Terrain" title=3D"Terrain">=
terrain</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Oceans" class=3D"m=
w-redirect" title=3D"Oceans">oceans</a>).  It is directly proportional to t=
he <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mass" title=3D"Mass">mass</a> o=
f air over that location.
</p><p>For numerical reasons, atmospheric models such as <a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/General_circulation_model" title=3D"General circulat=
ion model">general circulation models</a> (GCMs) usually predict the nondim=
ensional <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Logarithm" title=3D"Lo=
garithm">logarithm</a> of surface pressure</i>.
</p><p>The average value of surface pressure on Earth is 985 hPa.<sup id=3D=
"cite_ref-jacobs_8-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Atmospheric_pressure#cite_note-jacobs-8"><span class=3D"cite-bracke=
t">[</span>8<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> This is in cont=
rast to mean sea-level pressure, which involves the extrapolation of pressu=
re to sea level for locations above or below sea level. The average pressur=
e at mean sea level (<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sea_Level" cl=
ass=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Sea Level">MSL</a>) in the International Stand=
ard Atmosphere (<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/International_Stan=
dard_Atmosphere" title=3D"International Standard Atmosphere">ISA</a>) is 1,=
013.25 hPa, or 1 atmosphere (atm), or 29.92 inches of mercury.
</p><p>Pressure (P), mass (m), and acceleration due to gravity (g) are rela=
ted by P =3D F/A =3D (m*g)/A, where A is the surface area. Atmospheric pres=
sure is thus proportional to the weight per unit area of the atmospheric ma=
ss above that location.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Altitude_variation">Altitud=
e variation</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsectio=
