t was brought down towards sea level.</figcaption></figure>
<p>Pressure on Earth varies with the altitude of the surface, so air pressu=
re on mountains is usually lower than air pressure at sea level. Pressure v=
aries smoothly from the Earth's surface to the top of the <a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mesosphere" title=3D"Mesosphere">mesosphere</a>. Al=
though the pressure changes with the weather, NASA has averaged the conditi=
ons for all parts of the earth year-round. As altitude increases, atmospher=
ic pressure decreases. One can calculate the atmospheric pressure at a give=
n altitude.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-9" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Atmospheric_pressure#cite_note-9"><span class=3D"cite-b=
racket">[</span>9<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Temperatur=
e and humidity also affect the atmospheric pressure. Pressure is proportion=
al to temperature and inversely related to humidity, and both of these are =
necessary to compute an accurate figure. The graph <span class=3D"ifmobile"=
><span class=3D"nomobile">on the right</span><span class=3D"mobile">above</=
span></span> was developed for a temperature of 15&nbsp;=C2=B0C and a relat=
ive humidity of 0%.
</p><p>At low altitudes above sea level, the pressure decreases by about 1.=
2&nbsp;kPa (12&nbsp;hPa) for every 100 metres. For higher altitudes within =
the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Troposphere" title=3D"Troposph=
ere">troposphere</a>, the following equation (the <a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Barometric_formula" title=3D"Barometric formula">barometric=
 formula</a>) relates atmospheric pressure <i>p</i> to altitude <i>h</i>:
</p><p><br>
