<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Local_variation">Local vari=
ation</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-brac=
ket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DAtmosp=
heric_pressure&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D5" title=3D"Edit section: Lo=
cal variation"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">=
]</span></span></div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Wilma_2005-10-19_1315Z.jpg" class=3D"mw-file-=
description"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thu=
mb/0/00/Wilma_2005-10-19_1315Z.jpg/250px-Wilma_2005-10-19_1315Z.jpg" decodi=
ng=3D"async" width=3D"250" height=3D"156" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-fi=
le-width=3D"1920" data-file-height=3D"1200"></a><figcaption><a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hurricane_Wilma" title=3D"Hurricane Wilma">Hurric=
ane Wilma</a> on 19 October 2005. The pressure in the eye of the storm was =
882&nbsp;hPa (12.79&nbsp;psi) at the time the image was taken.</figcaption>=
</figure>
<p>Atmospheric pressure varies widely on Earth, and these changes are impor=
tant in studying <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Weather" title=3D=
"Weather">weather</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Climate"=
 title=3D"Climate">climate</a>. Atmospheric pressure shows a diurnal or sem=
idiurnal (twice-daily) cycle caused by global <a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Atmospheric_tides" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Atmospheric t=
ides">atmospheric tides</a>. This effect is strongest in tropical zones, wi=
th an amplitude of a few hectopascals, and almost zero in polar areas. Thes=
e variations have two superimposed cycles, a circadian (24&nbsp;h) cycle, a=
nd a semi-circadian (12&nbsp;h) cycle.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Records">Records</h2><span =
class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DAtmospheric_pressure&a=
mp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D6" title=3D"Edit section: Records"><span>edi=
t</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>The highest adjusted-to-sea level barometric pressure ever recorded on E=
arth (above 750 meters) was 1,084.8&nbsp;hPa (32.03&nbsp;inHg) measured in =
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tosontsengel,_Zavkhan" title=3D"To=
sontsengel, Zavkhan">Tosontsengel, Mongolia</a> on 19 December 2001.<sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-wmo.ASU.edu_10-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Atmospheric_pressure#cite_note-wmo.ASU.edu-10"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>10<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>=
 The highest adjusted-to-sea level barometric pressure ever recorded (below=
 750 meters) was at Agata in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Evenk=
_Autonomous_Okrug" title=3D"Evenk Autonomous Okrug">Evenk Autonomous Okrug<=
/a>, Russia (66=C2=B053'<span class=3D"nowrap">&nbsp;</span>N, 93=C2=B028'<=
span class=3D"nowrap">&nbsp;</span>E, elevation: 261&nbsp;m, 856&nbsp;ft) o=
n 31 December 1968 of 1,083.8&nbsp;hPa (32.005&nbsp;inHg).<sup id=3D"cite_r=
ef-11" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Atmosph=
eric_pressure#cite_note-11"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>11<span cl=
ass=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>  The discrimination is due to the p=
roblematic assumptions (assuming a standard lapse rate) associated with red=
uction of sea level from high elevations.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-wmo.ASU.edu_10=
-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Atmospheri=
c_pressure#cite_note-wmo.ASU.edu-10"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>1=
0<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dead_Sea" title=3D"Dead=
 Sea">Dead Sea</a>, the lowest place on Earth at 430 metres (1,410&nbsp;ft)=
 below sea level, has a correspondingly high typical atmospheric pressure o=
f 1,065<span class=3D"nowrap">&nbsp;</span>hPa.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-12" clas=
s=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Atmospheric_pressu=
re#cite_note-12"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>12<span class=3D"cite=
-bracket">]</span></a></sup> A below-sea-level surface pressure record of 1=
,081.8&nbsp;hPa (31.95&nbsp;inHg) was set on 21 February 1961.<sup id=3D"ci=
te_ref-13" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Atm=
ospheric_pressure#cite_note-13"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>13<spa=
n class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>The lowest non-tornadic atmospheric pressure ever measured was 870&n=
bsp;hPa (0.858&nbsp;atm; 25.69&nbsp;inHg), set on 12 October 1979, during <=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Typhoon_Tip" title=3D"Typhoon Tip">=
Typhoon Tip</a> in the western Pacific Ocean. The measurement was based on =
an instrumental observation made from a reconnaissance aircraft.<sup id=3D"=
cite_ref-FAQ1_14-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Atmospheric_pressure#cite_note-FAQ1-14"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">=
[</span>14<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Measurement_based_on_the_de=
pth_of_water">Measurement based on the depth of water</h2><span class=3D"mw=
-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DAtmospheric_pressure&amp;action=
=3Dedit&amp;section=3D7" title=3D"Edit section: Measurement based on the de=
pth of water"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]=
</span></span></div>
<p>One <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Atmosphere_(unit)" class=3D=
"mw-redirect" title=3D"Atmosphere (unit)">atmosphere</a> (101.325&nbsp;kPa =
or 14.7&nbsp;psi) is also the pressure caused by the weight of a column of =
freshwater of approximately 10.3&nbsp;m (33.8&nbsp;ft). Thus, a diver 10.3&=
nbsp;m under water experiences a pressure of about 2 atmospheres (1&nbsp;at=
m of air plus 1&nbsp;atm of water). Conversely, 10.3&nbsp;m is the maximum =
height to which water can be raised using <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Suction" title=3D"Suction">suction</a> under standard atmospheric c=
onditions.
</p><p>Low pressures, such as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Natu=
ral_gas" title=3D"Natural gas">natural gas</a> lines, are sometimes specifi=
ed in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Inch_of_water" title=3D"Inch=
 of water">inches of water</a>, typically written as <i>w.c.</i> (water col=
umn) gauge or <i>w.g.</i> (inches water) gauge. A typical gas-using residen=
tial appliance in the US is rated for a maximum of <span class=3D"frac"><sp=
an class=3D"num">1</span>=E2=81=84<span class=3D"den">2</span></span>&nbsp;=
psi (3.4&nbsp;kPa; 34&nbsp;mbar), which is approximately 14&nbsp;w.g. Simil=
ar metric units with a wide variety of names and notation based on <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Millimeters,_water_gauge" class=3D"mw-red=
irect" title=3D"Millimeters, water gauge">millimetres</a>, <a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Centimetre_of_water" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=
=3D"Centimetre of water">centimetres</a> or metres are now less commonly us=
ed.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Boiling_point_of_liquids">B=
oiling point of liquids</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"m=
w-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.=
php?title=3DAtmospheric_pressure&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D8" title=
=3D"Edit section: Boiling point of liquids"><span>edit</span></a><span clas=
s=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Kochendes_wasser02.jpg" class=3D"mw-file-desc=
ription"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1=
/18/Kochendes_wasser02.jpg/250px-Kochendes_wasser02.jpg" decoding=3D"async"=
 width=3D"250" height=3D"239" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"=
674" data-file-height=3D"644"></a><figcaption><a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Boiling_water" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Boiling water">Bo=
iling water</a></figcaption></figure>
<p>Pure water <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Boiling" title=3D"Bo=
iling">boils</a> at 100&nbsp;=C2=B0C (212&nbsp;=C2=B0F) at Earth's standard=
 atmospheric pressure. The boiling point is the temperature at which the <a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vapour_pressure" class=3D"mw-redirec=
t" title=3D"Vapour pressure">vapour pressure</a> is equal to the atmospheri=
c pressure around the liquid.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-15" class=3D"reference"><a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Atmospheric_pressure#cite_note-15"><=
span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>15<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span>=
</a></sup> Because of this, the boiling point of liquids is lower at lower =
pressure and higher at higher pressure. Cooking at high elevations, therefo=
re, requires adjustments to recipes<sup id=3D"cite_ref-16" class=3D"referen=
ce"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Atmospheric_pressure#cite_note=
-16"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>16<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]<=
/span></a></sup> or <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pressure_cooki=
ng" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Pressure cooking">pressure cooking</a>. =
A rough approximation of elevation can be obtained by measuring the tempera=
ture at which water boils; in the mid-19th century, this method was used by=
 explorers.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-17" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Atmospheric_pressure#cite_note-17"><span class=3D"cite=
-bracket">[</span>17<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Convers=
ely, if one wishes to evaporate a liquid at a lower temperature, for exampl=
e in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Distillation" title=3D"Distil=
lation">distillation</a>, the atmospheric pressure may be lowered by using =
a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vacuum_pump" title=3D"Vacuum pum=
p">vacuum pump</a>, as in a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rotary=
_evaporator" title=3D"Rotary evaporator">rotary evaporator</a>.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Measurement_and_maps">Measu=
rement and maps</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editse=
ction-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?titl=
e=3DAtmospheric_pressure&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D9" title=3D"Edit s=
ection: Measurement and maps"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editse=
ction-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>An important application of the knowledge that atmospheric pressure vari=
es directly with altitude was in determining the height of hills and mounta=
ins, thanks to reliable pressure measurement devices. In 1774, <a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nevil_Maskelyne" title=3D"Nevil Maskelyne">Nev=
il Maskelyne</a> was confirming Newton's theory of gravitation at and on <a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Schiehallion" title=3D"Schiehallion"=
>Schiehallion</a> mountain in Scotland, and he needed to measure elevations=
 on the mountain's sides accurately. This event is known as the <a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Schiehallion_experiment" title=3D"Schiehallio=
n experiment">Schiehallion experiment</a>. <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/William_Roy" title=3D"William Roy">William Roy</a>, using barometr=
ic pressure, was able to confirm Maskelyne's height determinations; the agr=
eement was within one meter (3.28 feet). This method became and continues t=
o be useful for survey work and map making.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-18" class=3D=
"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Atmospheric_pressure#c=
ite_note-18"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>18<span class=3D"cite-bra=
cket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
